{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17499788","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17499788"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:03:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:03:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1559"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1559","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1559"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.4,0.16,0.18,0.24,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1559"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97829"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1559","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1559"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1559"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80384"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"912"},{"type":"tags","id":"6610"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3183"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3210"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45167"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97829","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/97829"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old woman presents with a four week history of increasingly \u0022puffy\u0022 legs. She has no other associated symptoms and was feeling well until this began, apart from some 4 kg weight loss over the last two months. Her medical history includes hypertension, ischaemic heart disease and congestive cardiac failure. She is a non-smoker and does not drink alcohol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination her blood pressure is 100/70 mmHg, pulse 110/min and temperature 37.2C. There is an early diastolic murmur and lower limb oedema with no discernible limit. Her JVP is not elevated and her lungs are clear to auscultation. When exposing her abdomen, the below appearance is noted (image). Her abdomen is soft with no masses palpable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Budd-Chiari syndrome","Congestive cardiac failure exacerbation","Fulminant liver failure","Renal cell carcinoma","Retrosternal goitre"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe image demonstrates signs of \u003Cstrong\u003Einferior vena caval (IVC) obstruction\u003C/strong\u003E, namely marked dilatation of the superior and inferior epigastric vessels. This condition often presents with lower limb oedema and hypotension (if the obstruction is severe enough).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERenal cell carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely cause of IVC obstruction in this case. These tumours can extend directly into the IVC, where the obstruction may be due to progressive luminal occlusion rather than a mass effect of the primary tumour causing external compression of the IVC.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBudd-Chiari\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003Esyndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is an extremely rare condition. However, this case demonstrates none of the classical triad of the syndrome: acute-onset abdominal pain, massive ascites and hepatomegaly, and is therefore unlikely to be the diagnosis in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERetrosternal goitre\u003C/strong\u003E is a cause of SVC syndrome (compression of the SVC which causes head, face and arm venous congestion and oedema). Whilst it may lead to a collateral circulation with the inferior epigastric vessels, the predominant venous engorgement is in the head and chest.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Econgestive cardiac failure exacerbation\u003C/strong\u003E, while a reasonable differential for acute-onset lower limb oedema, is much less likely in this case, as there is no mention of other symptoms associated with cardiac failure (e.g. raised JVP, orthopnoea, paroxysmal nocturnal dyspnoea).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFulminant liver failure\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely to be the cause for the patient\u2019s IVC obstruction, as this condition would present more with symptoms of portal hypertension (e.g. caput medusae), which this image does not demonstrate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Inferior vena caval obstruction is a surgical emergency, resulting from both intrinsic and extrinsic causes.","Signs of inferior vena caval obstruction include dilatation of superior and inferior epigastric vessels."],"references":["Harris RD. The etiology of inferior vena caval obstruction and compression. CRC critical reviews in clinical radiology and nuclear medicine. 1976 Jan 1;8(1):57-86."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80384"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1559"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17797"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"17797","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17797"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/16de85c5-396c-40f9-aef4-7e5ab517c6aa.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/16de85c5-396c-40f9-aef4-7e5ab517c6aa.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":538}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80384","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/80384"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-09T17:02:00+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-09T10:21:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1559"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97829"}}},"meta":{"ca